  "prompt": "Knighthood: Is it possible for a non-native British citizen to be knighted?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible for a non-native British citizen to be knighted. While the honor is typically bestowed upon British citizens, there have been instances where non-British citizens have received knighthoods. \n\nWhen a non-British citizen is knighted, they are not referred to as \"Sir\" or \"Dame\" because they are not subjects of the British monarch. Instead, they use the title \"Knight\" or \"Dame\" before their name. For example, Bill Gates, co-founder of Microsoft, was awarded an honorary knighthood in 2005 and is referred to as \"Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire\" rather than \"Sir Bill Gates.\"\n\nTo be considered for a knighthood, individuals must have made a significant contribution to the UK or to British interests overseas. The nomination process typically involves a recommendation from the British government, which is then approved by the reigning monarch.",
